2008-10-08 
[LOC Somalia] ( SO ) ; [LOC Ukraine] ( UA ) ; [LOC Kenya] ( KE ) 
Crime ; weapons ; international ; money 
[MISC Somali] pirates who hijacked a [MISC Ukrainian] freighter carrying a large cargo of arms are approaching a deal for the ship 's release . 
Questions have emerged regarding the shipment of arms en route to [LOC Kenya] and of a possible clandestine arms deal between [LOC Kenya] and [LOC South Sudan] . 
On 08 October 2008 Maritime officials and associates of the [MISC Somali] pirates who on 25 September 2008 hijacked a [MISC Ukrainian] freighter carrying a large cargo of arms stated that the pirates may soon be collecting their ransom . 
After difficult negotiations likened by several people involved to bazaar-style haggling the parties are close to reaching a deal in which the pirates would be paid millions of dollars and the ship freed . 
A businessman in xarardheere , [LOC Somalia] named [PER Ahmed Omar] stated that the pirates and the ship owners have agreed on a ransom of approximately 8 million [LOC U.S.] dollars and the ship may be freed on 08 October 2008 or 09 October 2008 . 
Xarardheere is a notorious pirate base on the coast of [LOC Somalia] . 
Maritime officials in [LOC Kenya] stated that critical details have yet to be agreed upon . 
One such detail involves the pirates' request for a guarantee that they would not be arrested or attacked by the armada of [MISC American] warships currently encircling them . 
A [MISC Kenyan] maritime official stated anonymously that such negotiations are complex and involve more than the financial aspect . 
On 08 October 2008 the official stated that progress is being made and the parties are approaching an agreement . 
The pirates initially requested 35 million [LOC U.S.] dollars and then reduced their request to 20 million [LOC U.S.] dollars . 
The pirates have consistently expressed willingness to negotiate the financial figures . 
More than 25 ships have been hijacked in 2008 off the [LOC Somalia] coast with a typical ransom of between 1 and 2 million [LOC U.S.] dollars . 
The pirates aboard the [MISC Ukrainian] ship have stated that upon receipt of payment in [MISC American] dollars and preferably in 100 dollar bills the ship , its cargo and the 20 sailors on board will be released . 
The original country of destination for the arms shipment aboard the [MISC Ukrainian] ship is being questioned . 
Shortly after the freighter was hijacked on 25 September 2008 the [MISC Kenyan] government claimed that the weapons on board were being shipped for [LOC Kenya] 's military . 
The ship was en route to [LOC Kenya] 's main port of [LOC Mombasa] . 
The weapons on board the ship included 33 T-72 tanks , 150 grenade launchers , 6 anti-aircraft guns and a large quantity of ammunition . 
Evidence has subsequently emerged that the weapons were part of a clandestine arms deal between [LOC Kenya] and the separatist region of southern [LOC Sudan] . 
The deal would most likely have remained secret had the pirates not hijacked the ship and begun speaking to the media by satellite phone . 
[MISC Ukrainian] officials have been adamant in denying any wrongdoing . 
[MISC Ukrainian] diplomat in [LOC Kenya] oleh belokolos stated -- 
[LOC Ukraine] does not supply or have plans to supply any armaments to the [ORG Government of South Sudan] . 
All the appropriate paperwork has been validated . 
[LOC Ukraine] abides by all [ORG United Nations] rules and arms control agreements . 
[LOC Ukraine] inherited enormous stockpiles of weaponry after the collapse of the [LOC Soviet Union] and is now a major arms dealer . 
The deal with [LOC Ukraine] is considered suspicious given that [LOC Kenya] has mostly relied on the [LOC United Kingdom] and other western countries for its supply of heavy weapons . 
[MISC Kenyan] politicians were demanding answers and have called for several commissions to examine the situation . 
[LOC Southern Sudan] is an autonomous region that is currently increasing its military and that uses Soviet-designed tanks . 
[LOC The] [MISC American] military stated that its priority is to ensure that the weapons were not unloaded from the ship and sold to [MISC Islamist] insurgents in [LOC Somalia] . 
The pirates have denied interest in the weapons and claimed to have been unaware that the cargo included tanks when they hijacked the ship . 
Pirate spokesman [PER sugule Ali] stated in an interview last week that the pirates' sole interest in the deal is money . 
2008-11-28 
[LOC Afghanistan] ( AF ) 
Narcotics 
Head of the [ORG U.N.] drug office [PER Antonio Maria Costa] said that [LOC Afghanistan] has produced so much opium in recent years that the [ORG Taliban] are cutting back poppy cultivation and stockpiling raw opium in an effort to support prices and preserve a major source of financing for the insurgency . 
Head of the [ORG U.N.] drug office [PER Antonio Maria Costa] said that [LOC Afghanistan] has produced so much opium in recent years that the [ORG Taliban] are cutting back poppy cultivation and stockpiling raw opium in an effort to support prices and preserve a major source of financing for the insurgency . 
[ORG Costa] said this to reporters last week as the [ORG U.N. Drug Office Office] prepared to release its latest survey of [LOC Afghanistan] 's opium crop . 
The survey showed that poppy cultivation had retreated in much of [LOC Afghanistan] and was overwhelmingly concentrated in 7 of 34 provinces where the insurgency remains strong , most of those in the south . 
The survey was issued November 27 , 2008 . 
The [ORG United Nations] found that the result was a 19 percent reduction in the amount of land devoted to opium in [LOC Afghanistan] even though the total tonnage of opium produced dropped by just 6 percent . 
The study stated that the high output per acre was attributed to a good growing season in the south . 
The southern region is a heavily irrigated area where the [ORG Taliban] maintained a strong presence in 5 provinces and have systematically encouraged opium cultivation as a way to finance their insurgency for several years . 
The [ORG U.N.] estimates the insurgents made as much as 300 million dollars from the opium trade last year . 
[LOC Costa] said a lot of war effort can be funded with 2 to 300 million dollars . 
The [ORG Taliban] have producing an amount of opium that far exceeds world demand due to 3 successive years of bumper crops . 
[ORG Costa] said the result was a glut that was depressing the price , which dropped by approximately 20 percent . 
[LOC Costa] said that the fact that prices had not collapsed already was evidence that the [ORG Taliban] , drug lords and even some farmers have stockpiled the opium . 
An increasing amount is also being processed in [LOC Afghanistan] . 
[LOC Costa] added that insurgents have been holding significant amounts of opium . 
[ORG Costa] said the surplus is as much as 11000 tons , or more than twice world demand in the last 3 years and threatened to devalue their stockpiles . 
The [ORG United Nations] found that [LOC Afghanistan] produced 8500 tons of opium in 2008 . 
World demand was estimated at about 4400 tons per year . 
The [ORG Taliban] this year are taking a passive stance toward cultivation and putting less pressure on [MISC Afghan] farmers to plant opium poppy . 
This then supports the current price . 
[LOC Costa] is an [MISC Italian] diplomat who has served at the [ORG U.N. Office] on Drugs and Crime for 6 years . 
